{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti Chapter 1 specifies that the Kṛta (or Kr̥ta) Yuga itself lasts 4,000 divine years, with a preceding twilight (*sandhyāṁ pūrvām*) and following twilight (*uttarām*) each of 400 years (i.e., \"as many hundreds\" as the thousands of the yuga proper).[^1][^2]**\n\nThis gives a total duration for the full Kṛta Yuga period (yuga + twilights) of 4,800 years. The text presents this as an absolute measure in divine years (*devayuga*), not an explicit proportional ratio like 4:3:2:1 (which applies across the four yugas collectively). For context, the subsequent verse notes that the other yugas (Trētā, Dvāpara, Kali) have their thousands and hundreds successively reduced by 1 (e.g., Trētā: 3,000 + 300 + 300), yielding the familiar 12,000-year divine cycle (*caturyuga*).[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-a2767c).\n\n[^2]: Full verse: \"They say that four thousand years is the Krita Yuga; its twilight before is of as many hundreds, and its twilight after is of the same length. // Mn_1.69 //\"\n\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-85c454).",
